issue_body:
In the spring-boot-features.adoc documentation the Single Sign On section has a demo code that couldn't compile, because it refers to a non-existing method:
```java	
@Override
public void init(WebSecurity web) {
	web.ignore("/");
}
```

The the `WebSecurity.ignore(String ...)` method is not existing.

I replaced in my code with 

```java	
@Override
public void init(WebSecurity web) {
	web.ignoring().antMatchers("/");
}
```

and it worked. Pls let me know if I'm wrong or should I submit a PR to fix it.

I'm using Spring Boot 1.5.2.  

I have a `JsonApiMessageConverter` that I am trying to add to the `messageConverter` list.  I'm trying to follow the documentation at http://docs.spring.io/spring-boot/docs/current/reference/htmlsingle/#boot-features-spring-mvc-message-converters.

I have this config object:

```
@Configuration
public class MessageConverterConfig {

    @Autowired
    JsonApiMessageConverter jsonApiMessageConverter;

    @Bean
    public HttpMessageConverters customConverters() {
        return new HttpMessageConverters(false, Arrays.asList(jsonApiMessageConverter, new StringHttpMessageConverter()));
    }

}
```

I can set a break point in `customConverters` and see that its getting called.  However, another break point in `AbstractMessageConverterMethodProcessor` at line 224 shows that `this.messageConverters` does not contain my custom converters, so the default Jackson converter is used instead.

If I extend `WebMvcConfigurerAdapter` I can use `configureMessageConverters` or `extendMessageConverters` to add my custom converters without a problem.

The [Externalized Configuration section of the reference documentation](https://docs.spring.io/spring-boot/docs/2.6.x/reference/html/features.html#features.external-config)  say that order of default properties (`SpringApplication.setDefaultProperties()`) is lower with `@PropertySource`, but my test is  inconsistent.

My Spring Boot is 2.6.7.

-----
**My Test 1**

```java
@SpringBootApplication
@PropertySource(value = "classpath:/api.properties")
public class Demo6Application {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication application = new SpringApplication(Demo6Application.class);
        Properties properties = new Properties();
        properties.setProperty("api.name","default");
        application.setDefaultProperties(properties);
        ConfigurableApplicationContext run = application.run(args);
        String property = run.getEnvironment().getProperty("api.name");
        System.out.println(String.format("api.name=%s",property));
    }

}
```
api.properties
`api.name=api`

**My Result 1**

`api.name=default`

----

api.properties may be not loaded in My Test 1,so I print PropertySources of Environment in console.

-----

**My Test 2**

```java
@SpringBootApplication
@PropertySource(value = "classpath:/api.properties")
public class Demo6Application {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication application = new SpringApplication(Demo6Application.class);
        Properties properties = new Properties();
        properties.setProperty("api.name","default");
        application.setDefaultProperties(properties);
        ConfigurableApplicationContext run = application.run(args);
        run.getEnvironment().getPropertySources().forEach(System.out::println);
    }

}
```

**My Result 2**
```
ConfigurationPropertySourcesPropertySource {name='configurationProperties'}
PropertiesPropertySource {name='systemProperties'}
OriginAwareSystemEnvironmentPropertySource {name='systemEnvironment'}
RandomValuePropertySource {name='random'}
CachedRandomPropertySource {name='cachedrandom'}
MapPropertySource {name='springCloudClientHostInfo'}
DefaultPropertiesPropertySource {name='defaultProperties'}
